  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "To find integer solutions \\( (x, y) \\) to the equation \\( 167x + 113y = 1 \\), we can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm. This method finds integers \\( x \\) and \\( y \\) such that \\( ax + by = \\text{gcd}(a,b) \\).\n\n1. **Calculate \\( \\text{gcd}(167, 113) \\)** using the Euclidean algorithm:\n   \\[\n   167 = 113 \\cdot 1 + 54\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   113 = 54 \\cdot 2 + 5\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   54 = 5 \\cdot 10 + 4\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   5 = 4 \\cdot 1 + 1\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   4 = 1 \\cdot 4 + 0\n   \\]\n   The gcd is \\( 1 \\) (the last non-zero remainder).\n\n2. **Backtrack to express \\( 1 \\) as a combination of \\( 167 \\) and \\( 113 \\)**:\n   Starting from \\( 1 = 5 - 4 \\cdot 1 \\),\n   substitute \\( 4 \\):\n   \\[\n   1 = 5 - (54 - 5 \\cdot 10) = 11 \\cdot 5 - 54\n   \\]\n   Substitute \\( 5 \\):\n   \\[\n   1 = 11 \\cdot (113 - 54 \\cdot 2) - 54 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 22 \\cdot 54 - 54\n   \\]\n   Simplifying:\n   \\[\n   1 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 54\n   \\]\n   Substitute \\( 54 \\):\n   \\[\n   1 = 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot (167 - 113) = 34 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 167\n   \\]\n\nThus, we have found one particular solution:\n\\[\n(x_0, y_0) = (-23, 34)\n\\]\n\n3. **General solution**: The general solutions to the equation can be expressed as:\n\\[\nx = -23 + 113k\n\\]\n\\[\ny = 34 - 167k\n\\]\nfor any integer \\( k \\).\n\nThus, the integer solutions \\( (x, y) \\) to the equation \\( 167x + 113y = 1 \\) are given by:\n\\[\nx = -23 + 113k, \\quad y = 34 - 167k \\quad \\text{for any integer } k.\n\\]",
